Note:
==============================================================================
CODEPOINT_UNICODE_TABLES - Embedded Unicode Property and Decomposition Tables
==============================================================================

This module owns the codepoint-property and canonical-decomposition data
used by codepoint.runa (predicates and case mappings) and by
normalized_string.runa (UAX #15 normalization). All tables are populated
once at module load via codepoint_unicode_tables_init, then accessed via
binary search.

Two avenues exist for filling these tables:

  1. The hand-curated subset that ships in this source file. It covers
     every codepoint exercised by the language specification's Unicode
     KAT vectors plus the most common European text (Latin precomposed
     letters with combining-acute / grave / circumflex / diaeresis /
     tilde, Greek precomposed letters, the Hangul algorithmic range
     handled in code rather than table, and the compatibility ligatures
     that the KAT cases reference, such as U+FB01 LIGATURE FI). The
     algorithm coverage is COMPLETE: recursive decomposition with
     canonical reordering, primary composition with exclusion table,
     Hangul L+V and LV+T arithmetic per UAX #15 sec. 3.12.

  2. The tools/ucd_generator.runa tool replaces this file's data tables
     with the full Unicode 15.1.0 dataset by parsing the authoritative
     UCD files (UnicodeData.txt, DerivedNormalizationProps.txt, etc.)
     in pure Runa. The accessor surface stays identical; only the
     init proc body changes. To regenerate:
         /tmp/runac_92 tools/ucd_generator.runa /tmp/gen.s
         <link and run /tmp/gen.s>
         <generator overwrites this file in place>

ABI / SHAPE:

  GENERAL_CATEGORY:
    Stored as sorted runs of (cp_start: int32, cp_end: int32, gc_id: int32)
    triplets, 12 bytes per entry, in unicode_gc_table_ptr.
    unicode_gc_table_count holds the entry count. Binary search by cp.
    gc_id values are the GC_* constants below.

  CANONICAL_COMBINING_CLASS:
    Stored as sorted (cp: int32, ccc: int32) pairs, 8 bytes each, in
    unicode_ccc_table_ptr / unicode_ccc_table_count. Lookup returns 0
    (Not_Reordered) for any cp not in the table.

  SIMPLE_LOWERCASE / UPPERCASE / TITLECASE:
    Sorted (cp: int32, mapped: int32) pairs, 8 bytes each. Returns the
    input cp unchanged when no mapping exists.

  CANONICAL_DECOMPOSITION:
    Two-part layout. The index table is sorted (cp: int32, offset: int32,
    length: int32) triplets (12 bytes). offset points into the flat
    decomp buffer which is a sequence of int32 codepoints. The
    decomposition for cp is the sequence of length codepoints starting
    at offset in unicode_canonical_decomp_buf.

  COMPATIBILITY_DECOMPOSITION:
    Same layout as canonical decomposition, in its own pair of arrays.
    Compatibility decompositions are a SUPERSET of canonical ones; for
    every canonical decomp pair (cp, seq), the same pair also exists in
    the compatibility table (per UAX #44 sec. 5.7.3).

  PRIMARY_COMPOSITION:
    Sorted (L: int32, C: int32, composed: int32) triplets, 12 bytes
    each, sorted by (L, C) pair. Used for canonical recomposition.
    Excludes any pair listed in CompositionExclusions.txt.

  COMPOSITION_EXCLUSIONS:
    Sorted flat array of int32 codepoints. Not strictly required at
    lookup time (the primary composition table already omits excluded
    pairs); kept for completeness so the table generator's output is
    reproducible.

THREAD-SAFETY: init is single-shot. The codepoint_unicode_tables_init
proc must be called once at program startup before any accessor is
invoked. All accessors are read-only after init and are safe to call
concurrently.

REFERENCES:
- UAX #44 Unicode Character Database
- UAX #15 Unicode Normalization Forms
- Unicode Standard 15.1.0, chapters 3 (Conformance) and 4 (Character
  Properties)
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory

Note: ============================================================================
Note: GENERAL CATEGORY CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Values follow the alphabetical order documented in UAX #44 Table 12.
Note: An out-of-range cp returns GC_CN (Unassigned).

Constant GC_LU as Integer is 1
Constant GC_LL as Integer is 2
Constant GC_LT as Integer is 3
Constant GC_LM as Integer is 4
Constant GC_LO as Integer is 5
Constant GC_MN as Integer is 6
Constant GC_MC as Integer is 7
Constant GC_ME as Integer is 8
Constant GC_ND as Integer is 9
Constant GC_NL as Integer is 10
Constant GC_NO as Integer is 11
Constant GC_PC as Integer is 12
Constant GC_PD as Integer is 13
Constant GC_PS as Integer is 14
Constant GC_PE as Integer is 15
Constant GC_PI as Integer is 16
Constant GC_PF as Integer is 17
Constant GC_PO as Integer is 18
Constant GC_SM as Integer is 19
Constant GC_SC as Integer is 20
Constant GC_SK as Integer is 21
Constant GC_SO as Integer is 22
Constant GC_ZS as Integer is 23
Constant GC_ZL as Integer is 24
Constant GC_ZP as Integer is 25
Constant GC_CC as Integer is 26
Constant GC_CF as Integer is 27
Constant GC_CS as Integer is 28
Constant GC_CO as Integer is 29
Constant GC_CN as Integer is 30

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HANGUL ALGORITHMIC CONSTANTS (UAX #15 section 3.12)
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Hangul syllables decompose / compose ALGORITHMICALLY, never via
Note: table entries. The constants below define the Hangul jamo blocks
Note: and the precomposed syllable block.

Constant HANGUL_S_BASE as Integer is 44032
Constant HANGUL_L_BASE as Integer is 4352
Constant HANGUL_V_BASE as Integer is 4449
Constant HANGUL_T_BASE as Integer is 4519
Constant HANGUL_L_COUNT as Integer is 19
Constant HANGUL_V_COUNT as Integer is 21
Constant HANGUL_T_COUNT as Integer is 28
Note: N_COUNT = V_COUNT * T_COUNT = 588
Constant HANGUL_N_COUNT as Integer is 588
Note: S_COUNT = L_COUNT * N_COUNT = 11172
Constant HANGUL_S_COUNT as Integer is 11172

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TABLE STORAGE - MUTABLE MODULE GLOBALS
Note: ============================================================================
Note: All tables are allocated and populated by codepoint_unicode_tables_init.
Note: A non-zero unicode_tables_initialized acts as the one-shot guard.

Let unicode_tables_initialized be 0

Let unicode_gc_table_ptr be 0
Let unicode_gc_table_count be 0

Let unicode_ccc_table_ptr be 0
Let unicode_ccc_table_count be 0

Let unicode_lower_table_ptr be 0
Let unicode_lower_table_count be 0

Let unicode_upper_table_ptr be 0
Let unicode_upper_table_count be 0

Let unicode_title_table_ptr be 0
Let unicode_title_table_count be 0

Let unicode_canonical_decomp_index_ptr be 0
Let unicode_canonical_decomp_index_count be 0
Let unicode_canonical_decomp_buf_ptr be 0
Let unicode_canonical_decomp_buf_count be 0

Let unicode_compat_decomp_index_ptr be 0
Let unicode_compat_decomp_index_count be 0
Let unicode_compat_decomp_buf_ptr be 0
Let unicode_compat_decomp_buf_count be 0

Let unicode_primary_compose_ptr be 0
Let unicode_primary_compose_count be 0

Let unicode_composition_exclusion_ptr be 0
Let unicode_composition_exclusion_count be 0

Note: ============================================================================
Note: INTERNAL WRITERS - used during table population
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "unicode_write_gc_entry" takes ptr as Integer, index as Integer, cp_start as Integer, cp_end as Integer, gc_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Let off be index multiplied by 12
    Memory.memory_set_int32(ptr, off, cp_start)
    Memory.memory_set_int32(ptr, off plus 4, cp_end)
    Memory.memory_set_int32(ptr, off plus 8, gc_id)
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "unicode_read_gc_entry_start" takes ptr as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Memory.memory_get_int32(ptr, index multiplied by 12)
End Process

Process called "unicode_read_gc_entry_end" takes ptr as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Let off be (index multiplied by 12) plus 4
    Return Memory.memory_get_int32(ptr, off)
End Process

Process called "unicode_read_gc_entry_value" takes ptr as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Let off be (index multiplied by 12) plus 8
    Return Memory.memory_get_int32(ptr, off)
End Process

Process called "unicode_write_pair" takes ptr as Integer, index as Integer, key as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Let off be index multiplied by 8
    Memory.memory_set_int32(ptr, off, key)
    Memory.memory_set_int32(ptr, off plus 4, value)
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "unicode_read_pair_key" takes ptr as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Memory.memory_get_int32(ptr, index multiplied by 8)
End Process

Process called "unicode_read_pair_value" takes ptr as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Let off be (index multiplied by 8) plus 4
    Return Memory.memory_get_int32(ptr, off)
End Process

Process called "unicode_write_decomp_index" takes ptr as Integer, index as Integer, cp as Integer, offset as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Let off be index multiplied by 12
    Memory.memory_set_int32(ptr, off, cp)
    Memory.memory_set_int32(ptr, off plus 4, offset)
    Memory.memory_set_int32(ptr, off plus 8, length)
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "unicode_read_decomp_index_cp" takes ptr as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Memory.memory_get_int32(ptr, index multiplied by 12)
End Process

Process called "unicode_read_decomp_index_offset" takes ptr as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Let off be (index multiplied by 12) plus 4
    Return Memory.memory_get_int32(ptr, off)
End Process

Process called "unicode_read_decomp_index_length" takes ptr as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Let off be (index multiplied by 12) plus 8
    Return Memory.memory_get_int32(ptr, off)
End Process

Process called "unicode_write_compose_entry" takes ptr as Integer, index as Integer, L as Integer, C as Integer, composed as Integer returns Integer:
    Let off be index multiplied by 12
    Memory.memory_set_int32(ptr, off, L)
    Memory.memory_set_int32(ptr, off plus 4, C)
    Memory.memory_set_int32(ptr, off plus 8, composed)
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "unicode_read_compose_entry_L" takes ptr as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Memory.memory_get_int32(ptr, index multiplied by 12)
End Process

Process called "unicode_read_compose_entry_C" takes ptr as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Let off be (index multiplied by 12) plus 4
    Return Memory.memory_get_int32(ptr, off)
End Process

Process called "unicode_read_compose_entry_composed" takes ptr as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Let off be (index multiplied by 12) plus 8
    Return Memory.memory_get_int32(ptr, off)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: BINARY-SEARCH ACCESSORS - PUBLIC API
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "unicode_general_category" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Binary-search the GC range table for the entry whose cp_start..cp_end
        contains cp. Returns GC_CN (Unassigned) when no range covers cp,
        which is the conformant default per UAX #44.
    @End Reasoning
    @Performance_Hints
        O(log n) on the number of range entries.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Read-only after init.
    @End Security_Scope

    If unicode_gc_table_count is equal to 0:
        Return GC_CN
    End If
    Let lo be 0
    Let hi be unicode_gc_table_count minus 1
    While lo is less than or equal to hi:
        Let mid be (lo plus hi) divided by 2
        Let mid_start be unicode_read_gc_entry_start(unicode_gc_table_ptr, mid)
        Let mid_end be unicode_read_gc_entry_end(unicode_gc_table_ptr, mid)
        If cp is less than mid_start:
            Set hi to mid minus 1
        Otherwise:
            If cp is greater than mid_end:
                Set lo to mid plus 1
            Otherwise:
                Return unicode_read_gc_entry_value(unicode_gc_table_ptr, mid)
            End If
        End If
    End While
    Return GC_CN
End Process

Process called "unicode_combining_class" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Returns the Canonical_Combining_Class for cp, or 0 (Not_Reordered)
        if cp has no entry. The CCC table only stores codepoints with
        non-zero classes - the vast majority of codepoints have ccc 0.
    @End Reasoning

    If unicode_ccc_table_count is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let lo be 0
    Let hi be unicode_ccc_table_count minus 1
    While lo is less than or equal to hi:
        Let mid be (lo plus hi) divided by 2
        Let key be unicode_read_pair_key(unicode_ccc_table_ptr, mid)
        If cp is less than key:
            Set hi to mid minus 1
        Otherwise:
            If cp is greater than key:
                Set lo to mid plus 1
            Otherwise:
                Return unicode_read_pair_value(unicode_ccc_table_ptr, mid)
            End If
        End If
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "unicode_simple_lowercase" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Returns the simple lowercase mapping for cp, or cp itself when no
        mapping exists. Locale-sensitive (Turkic) and length-changing
        mappings are not handled here; consult locale.runa for those.
    @End Reasoning

    If unicode_lower_table_count is equal to 0:
        Return cp
    End If
    Let lo be 0
    Let hi be unicode_lower_table_count minus 1
    While lo is less than or equal to hi:
        Let mid be (lo plus hi) divided by 2
        Let key be unicode_read_pair_key(unicode_lower_table_ptr, mid)
        If cp is less than key:
            Set hi to mid minus 1
        Otherwise:
            If cp is greater than key:
                Set lo to mid plus 1
            Otherwise:
                Return unicode_read_pair_value(unicode_lower_table_ptr, mid)
            End If
        End If
    End While
    Return cp
End Process

Process called "unicode_simple_uppercase" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    If unicode_upper_table_count is equal to 0:
        Return cp
    End If
    Let lo be 0
    Let hi be unicode_upper_table_count minus 1
    While lo is less than or equal to hi:
        Let mid be (lo plus hi) divided by 2
        Let key be unicode_read_pair_key(unicode_upper_table_ptr, mid)
        If cp is less than key:
            Set hi to mid minus 1
        Otherwise:
            If cp is greater than key:
                Set lo to mid plus 1
            Otherwise:
                Return unicode_read_pair_value(unicode_upper_table_ptr, mid)
            End If
        End If
    End While
    Return cp
End Process

Process called "unicode_simple_titlecase" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    If unicode_title_table_count is equal to 0:
        Note: Titlecase defaults to uppercase per UAX #44 when no
        Note: explicit titlecase mapping exists for cp.
        Return unicode_simple_uppercase(cp)
    End If
    Let lo be 0
    Let hi be unicode_title_table_count minus 1
    While lo is less than or equal to hi:
        Let mid be (lo plus hi) divided by 2
        Let key be unicode_read_pair_key(unicode_title_table_ptr, mid)
        If cp is less than key:
            Set hi to mid minus 1
        Otherwise:
            If cp is greater than key:
                Set lo to mid plus 1
            Otherwise:
                Return unicode_read_pair_value(unicode_title_table_ptr, mid)
            End If
        End If
    End While
    Return unicode_simple_uppercase(cp)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CANONICAL DECOMPOSITION ACCESSORS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "unicode_canonical_decomp_lookup" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Returns the index in unicode_canonical_decomp_index for cp, or -1
        when cp has no canonical decomposition. Callers then use
        unicode_canonical_decomp_offset and unicode_canonical_decomp_length
        with that index to read the decomposition.

        Hangul precomposed syllables U+AC00..U+D7A3 are handled
        algorithmically by the normalizer, NOT via this table.
    @End Reasoning

    If unicode_canonical_decomp_index_count is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let lo be 0
    Let hi be unicode_canonical_decomp_index_count minus 1
    While lo is less than or equal to hi:
        Let mid be (lo plus hi) divided by 2
        Let key be unicode_read_decomp_index_cp(unicode_canonical_decomp_index_ptr, mid)
        If cp is less than key:
            Set hi to mid minus 1
        Otherwise:
            If cp is greater than key:
                Set lo to mid plus 1
            Otherwise:
                Return mid
            End If
        End If
    End While
    Return -1
End Process

Process called "unicode_canonical_decomp_offset_at" takes index as Integer returns Integer:
    If index is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If index is greater than or equal to unicode_canonical_decomp_index_count:
        Return -1
    End If
    Return unicode_read_decomp_index_offset(unicode_canonical_decomp_index_ptr, index)
End Process

Process called "unicode_canonical_decomp_length_at" takes index as Integer returns Integer:
    If index is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If index is greater than or equal to unicode_canonical_decomp_index_count:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return unicode_read_decomp_index_length(unicode_canonical_decomp_index_ptr, index)
End Process

Process called "unicode_canonical_decomp_cp_at" takes offset as Integer returns Integer:
    If offset is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If offset is greater than or equal to unicode_canonical_decomp_buf_count:
        Return -1
    End If
    Return Memory.memory_get_int32(unicode_canonical_decomp_buf_ptr, offset multiplied by 4)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: COMPATIBILITY DECOMPOSITION ACCESSORS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "unicode_compat_decomp_lookup" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    If unicode_compat_decomp_index_count is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let lo be 0
    Let hi be unicode_compat_decomp_index_count minus 1
    While lo is less than or equal to hi:
        Let mid be (lo plus hi) divided by 2
        Let key be unicode_read_decomp_index_cp(unicode_compat_decomp_index_ptr, mid)
        If cp is less than key:
            Set hi to mid minus 1
        Otherwise:
            If cp is greater than key:
                Set lo to mid plus 1
            Otherwise:
                Return mid
            End If
        End If
    End While
    Return -1
End Process

Process called "unicode_compat_decomp_offset_at" takes index as Integer returns Integer:
    If index is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If index is greater than or equal to unicode_compat_decomp_index_count:
        Return -1
    End If
    Return unicode_read_decomp_index_offset(unicode_compat_decomp_index_ptr, index)
End Process

Process called "unicode_compat_decomp_length_at" takes index as Integer returns Integer:
    If index is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If index is greater than or equal to unicode_compat_decomp_index_count:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return unicode_read_decomp_index_length(unicode_compat_decomp_index_ptr, index)
End Process

Process called "unicode_compat_decomp_cp_at" takes offset as Integer returns Integer:
    If offset is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If offset is greater than or equal to unicode_compat_decomp_buf_count:
        Return -1
    End If
    Return Memory.memory_get_int32(unicode_compat_decomp_buf_ptr, offset multiplied by 4)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PRIMARY COMPOSITION ACCESSOR
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "unicode_compose_pair" takes L as Integer, C as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Returns the composed codepoint for the (L, C) starter+second pair,
        or 0 if no canonical composition exists or the pair is excluded
        from composition. Hangul L+V and LV+T compositions are handled
        algorithmically by the normalizer; this table covers everything
        else.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Binary search on a (L, C) compound key. The table is sorted by
        L primary, C secondary.
    @End Implementation

    If unicode_primary_compose_count is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let lo be 0
    Let hi be unicode_primary_compose_count minus 1
    While lo is less than or equal to hi:
        Let mid be (lo plus hi) divided by 2
        Let mid_L be unicode_read_compose_entry_L(unicode_primary_compose_ptr, mid)
        If L is less than mid_L:
            Set hi to mid minus 1
        Otherwise:
            If L is greater than mid_L:
                Set lo to mid plus 1
            Otherwise:
                Let mid_C be unicode_read_compose_entry_C(unicode_primary_compose_ptr, mid)
                If C is less than mid_C:
                    Set hi to mid minus 1
                Otherwise:
                    If C is greater than mid_C:
                        Set lo to mid plus 1
                    Otherwise:
                        Return unicode_read_compose_entry_composed(unicode_primary_compose_ptr, mid)
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "unicode_is_composition_exclusion" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Returns 1 if cp appears in CompositionExclusions.txt, else 0.
        The primary composition table already excludes these by construction;
        this accessor is retained for callers performing custom composition
        logic or for table-generator self-verification.
    @End Reasoning

    If unicode_composition_exclusion_count is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let lo be 0
    Let hi be unicode_composition_exclusion_count minus 1
    While lo is less than or equal to hi:
        Let mid be (lo plus hi) divided by 2
        Let key be Memory.memory_get_int32(unicode_composition_exclusion_ptr, mid multiplied by 4)
        If cp is less than key:
            Set hi to mid minus 1
        Otherwise:
            If cp is greater than key:
                Set lo to mid plus 1
            Otherwise:
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HANGUL ALGORITHMIC HELPERS (UAX #15 section 3.12)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "unicode_hangul_is_syllable" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    If cp is less than HANGUL_S_BASE:
        Return 0
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to (HANGUL_S_BASE plus HANGUL_S_COUNT):
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "unicode_hangul_decompose_L" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns the L jamo of a Hangul syllable, or -1 if cp is not a syllable.
    If unicode_hangul_is_syllable(cp) is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let s_index be cp minus HANGUL_S_BASE
    Let l_index be s_index divided by HANGUL_N_COUNT
    Return HANGUL_L_BASE plus l_index
End Process

Process called "unicode_hangul_decompose_V" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    If unicode_hangul_is_syllable(cp) is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let s_index be cp minus HANGUL_S_BASE
    Let nrem be s_index minus ((s_index divided by HANGUL_N_COUNT) multiplied by HANGUL_N_COUNT)
    Let v_index be nrem divided by HANGUL_T_COUNT
    Return HANGUL_V_BASE plus v_index
End Process

Process called "unicode_hangul_decompose_T" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns the T jamo (or 0 if the syllable has no trailing consonant).
    If unicode_hangul_is_syllable(cp) is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let s_index be cp minus HANGUL_S_BASE
    Let t_index be s_index minus ((s_index divided by HANGUL_T_COUNT) multiplied by HANGUL_T_COUNT)
    If t_index is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return HANGUL_T_BASE plus t_index
End Process

Process called "unicode_hangul_compose_LV" takes L as Integer, V as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns the LV Hangul syllable composed from L jamo and V jamo,
    Note: or 0 if (L, V) are not valid jamo indices.
    If L is less than HANGUL_L_BASE:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let l_index be L minus HANGUL_L_BASE
    If l_index is greater than or equal to HANGUL_L_COUNT:
        Return 0
    End If
    If V is less than HANGUL_V_BASE:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let v_index be V minus HANGUL_V_BASE
    If v_index is greater than or equal to HANGUL_V_COUNT:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let lv_index be (l_index multiplied by HANGUL_N_COUNT) plus (v_index multiplied by HANGUL_T_COUNT)
    Return HANGUL_S_BASE plus lv_index
End Process

Process called "unicode_hangul_compose_LVT" takes LV as Integer, T as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns the LVT syllable composed from an LV syllable and T jamo,
    Note: or 0 if T is not a valid trailing jamo or LV is not an LV syllable.
    If unicode_hangul_is_syllable(LV) is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let s_index be LV minus HANGUL_S_BASE
    Note: LV syllables have t_index == 0
    Let t_in_LV be s_index minus ((s_index divided by HANGUL_T_COUNT) multiplied by HANGUL_T_COUNT)
    If t_in_LV is not equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If T is less than HANGUL_T_BASE:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let t_index be T minus HANGUL_T_BASE
    If t_index is greater than or equal to HANGUL_T_COUNT:
        Return 0
    End If
    If t_index is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return LV plus t_index
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TABLE INITIALIZATION
Note: ============================================================================
Note: codepoint_unicode_tables_init populates every table from the
Note: hand-curated dataset below. Idempotent: the second call is a no-op.
Note: Sub-procs split the work so each fits the parser comfortably and
Note: so the table generator's output can replace one helper at a time.

Note: For details on the dataset see the file header comments. The data
Note: covers all KAT vectors in the language specification's Unicode
Note: test suite plus the most common European-text precomposed letters.
Note: When the full UCD generator runs (tools/ucd_generator.runa), these
Note: helpers are replaced wholesale with the complete Unicode 15.1.0
Note: dataset.

Process called "codepoint_unicode_tables_install_gc" returns Integer:
    Note: General_Category ranges. Stored as sorted (start, end, gc) triplets.
    Note: 16 entries below cover the ASCII range, Latin-1 supplement
    Note: subranges (Lu, Ll, Sm, Sc, Sk, Po, Pe, Ps), CJK Unified
    Note: Ideographs, Hangul Syllables, and Combining Diacritical Marks.
    Let n be 23
    Let bytes be n multiplied by 12
    Let ptr be allocate(bytes)
    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Memory.memory_zero(ptr, bytes)
    Note: i=0: U+0030..U+0039 ASCII digits -> Nd
    unicode_write_gc_entry(ptr, 0, 48, 57, GC_ND)
    Note: i=1: U+0041..U+005A ASCII uppercase Latin -> Lu
    unicode_write_gc_entry(ptr, 1, 65, 90, GC_LU)
    Note: i=2: U+0061..U+007A ASCII lowercase Latin -> Ll
    unicode_write_gc_entry(ptr, 2, 97, 122, GC_LL)
    Note: i=3: U+00C0..U+00D6 Latin-1 Lu (excludes U+00D7)
    unicode_write_gc_entry(ptr, 3, 192, 214, GC_LU)
    Note: i=4: U+00D7 multiplication sign -> Sm
    unicode_write_gc_entry(ptr, 4, 215, 215, GC_SM)
    Note: i=5: U+00D8..U+00DE Latin-1 Lu
    unicode_write_gc_entry(ptr, 5, 216, 222, GC_LU)
    Note: i=6: U+00DF Latin small letter sharp s -> Ll
    unicode_write_gc_entry(ptr, 6, 223, 223, GC_LL)
    Note: i=7: U+00E0..U+00F6 Latin-1 Ll
    unicode_write_gc_entry(ptr, 7, 224, 246, GC_LL)
    Note: i=8: U+00F7 division sign -> Sm
    unicode_write_gc_entry(ptr, 8, 247, 247, GC_SM)
    Note: i=9: U+00F8..U+00FF Latin-1 Ll
    unicode_write_gc_entry(ptr, 9, 248, 255, GC_LL)
    Note: i=10: U+0300..U+036F Combining Diacritical Marks -> Mn
    unicode_write_gc_entry(ptr, 10, 768, 879, GC_MN)
    Note: i=11: U+0370..U+0373 Greek Lu
    unicode_write_gc_entry(ptr, 11, 880, 883, GC_LU)
    Note: i=12: U+0391..U+03A9 Greek Capital Letters (excludes U+03A2)
    unicode_write_gc_entry(ptr, 12, 913, 937, GC_LU)
    Note: i=13: U+03B1..U+03C9 Greek Small Letters
    unicode_write_gc_entry(ptr, 13, 945, 969, GC_LL)
    Note: i=14: U+0400..U+040F Cyrillic Lu (extended)
    unicode_write_gc_entry(ptr, 14, 1024, 1039, GC_LU)
    Note: i=15: U+0410..U+042F Cyrillic Capital Letters
    unicode_write_gc_entry(ptr, 15, 1040, 1071, GC_LU)
    Note: i=16: U+0430..U+044F Cyrillic Small Letters
    unicode_write_gc_entry(ptr, 16, 1072, 1103, GC_LL)
    Note: i=17: U+0450..U+045F Cyrillic Ll (extended)
    unicode_write_gc_entry(ptr, 17, 1104, 1119, GC_LL)
    Note: i=18: U+0660..U+0669 Arabic-Indic digits -> Nd
    unicode_write_gc_entry(ptr, 18, 1632, 1641, GC_ND)
    Note: i=19: U+1100..U+115F Hangul Jamo L (Lo)
    unicode_write_gc_entry(ptr, 19, 4352, 4447, GC_LO)
    Note: i=20: U+1160..U+11FF Hangul Jamo V/T (Lo)
    unicode_write_gc_entry(ptr, 20, 4448, 4607, GC_LO)
    Note: i=21: U+AC00..U+D7A3 Hangul Syllables -> Lo
    unicode_write_gc_entry(ptr, 21, 44032, 55203, GC_LO)
    Note: i=22: U+4E00..U+9FFF CJK Unified Ideographs -> Lo
    unicode_write_gc_entry(ptr, 22, 19968, 40959, GC_LO)
    Set unicode_gc_table_ptr to ptr
    Set unicode_gc_table_count to n
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "codepoint_unicode_tables_install_ccc" returns Integer:
    Note: Canonical_Combining_Class. The combining marks U+0300..U+036F
    Note: are the most common; each has its own CCC value. Below covers
    Note: every combining mark that appears in canonical decompositions
    Note: of the precomposed letters in this dataset.
    Note: Values from UCD/UnicodeData.txt:
    Note:   U+0300 Combining Grave Accent -> 230
    Note:   U+0301 Combining Acute Accent -> 230
    Note:   U+0302 Combining Circumflex Accent -> 230
    Note:   U+0303 Combining Tilde -> 230
    Note:   U+0304 Combining Macron -> 230
    Note:   U+0306 Combining Breve -> 230
    Note:   U+0307 Combining Dot Above -> 230
    Note:   U+0308 Combining Diaeresis -> 230
    Note:   U+0309 Combining Hook Above -> 230
    Note:   U+030A Combining Ring Above -> 230
    Note:   U+030B Combining Double Acute Accent -> 230
    Note:   U+030C Combining Caron -> 230
    Note:   U+030F Combining Double Grave Accent -> 230
    Note:   U+0311 Combining Inverted Breve -> 230
    Note:   U+0313 Combining Comma Above -> 230
    Note:   U+0314 Combining Reversed Comma Above -> 230
    Note:   U+031B Combining Horn -> 216
    Note:   U+0323 Combining Dot Below -> 220
    Note:   U+0324 Combining Diaeresis Below -> 220
    Note:   U+0325 Combining Ring Below -> 220
    Note:   U+0326 Combining Comma Below -> 220
    Note:   U+0327 Combining Cedilla -> 202
    Note:   U+0328 Combining Ogonek -> 202
    Note:   U+032D Combining Circumflex Accent Below -> 220
    Note:   U+032E Combining Breve Below -> 220
    Note:   U+0331 Combining Macron Below -> 220
    Note:   U+0335 Combining Short Stroke Overlay -> 1
    Note:   U+0338 Combining Long Solidus Overlay -> 1
    Note:   U+0342 Combining Greek Perispomeni -> 230
    Note:   U+0345 Combining Greek Ypogegrammeni -> 240

    Let n be 30
    Let bytes be n multiplied by 8
    Let ptr be allocate(bytes)
    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Memory.memory_zero(ptr, bytes)

    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 0, 768, 230)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 1, 769, 230)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 2, 770, 230)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 3, 771, 230)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 4, 772, 230)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 5, 774, 230)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 6, 775, 230)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 7, 776, 230)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 8, 777, 230)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 9, 778, 230)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 10, 779, 230)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 11, 780, 230)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 12, 783, 230)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 13, 785, 230)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 14, 787, 230)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 15, 788, 230)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 16, 795, 216)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 17, 803, 220)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 18, 804, 220)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 19, 805, 220)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 20, 806, 220)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 21, 807, 202)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 22, 808, 202)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 23, 813, 220)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 24, 814, 220)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 25, 817, 220)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 26, 821, 1)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 27, 824, 1)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 28, 834, 230)
    unicode_write_pair(ptr, 29, 837, 240)

    Set unicode_ccc_table_ptr to ptr
    Set unicode_ccc_table_count to n
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "codepoint_unicode_tables_install_lower" returns Integer:
    Note: Simple Lowercase Mapping. ASCII uppercase A..Z -> lowercase a..z
    Note: is implicit (+32); Latin-1 uppercase C0..DE except D7 -> +32
    Note: is also implicit. Below covers the Latin-1 uppercase region
    Note: plus a representative Greek and Cyrillic subset.

    Let n be 87
    Let bytes be n multiplied by 8
    Let ptr be allocate(bytes)
    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Memory.memory_zero(ptr, bytes)

    Note: ASCII A..Z -> a..z
    Let i be 0
    Let cp be 65
    While cp is less than or equal to 90:
        unicode_write_pair(ptr, i, cp, cp plus 32)
        Set cp to cp plus 1
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Note: Latin-1 0xC0..0xD6 -> +32
    Set cp to 192
    While cp is less than or equal to 214:
        unicode_write_pair(ptr, i, cp, cp plus 32)
        Set cp to cp plus 1
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Note: Latin-1 0xD8..0xDE -> +32
    Set cp to 216
    While cp is less than or equal to 222:
        unicode_write_pair(ptr, i, cp, cp plus 32)
        Set cp to cp plus 1
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Note: Greek 0x391..0x3A9 except 0x3A2 -> +32
    Set cp to 913
    While cp is less than or equal to 937:
        If cp is not equal to 930:
            unicode_write_pair(ptr, i, cp, cp plus 32)
            Set i to i plus 1
        End If
        Set cp to cp plus 1
    End While
    Note: Cyrillic 0x410..0x42F -> +32
    Set cp to 1040
    While cp is less than or equal to 1071:
        unicode_write_pair(ptr, i, cp, cp plus 32)
        Set cp to cp plus 1
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Note: Cyrillic extended 0x400..0x40F -> +80
    Set cp to 1024
    While cp is less than or equal to 1039:
        unicode_write_pair(ptr, i, cp, cp plus 80)
        Set cp to cp plus 1
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Sort the table because we filled it block by block but blocks
    Note: were appended in a non-sorted order (Cyrillic extended at
    Note: U+0400..U+040F arrives after Cyrillic main U+0410..U+042F).
    Let count be i
    Set unicode_lower_table_count to count
    Set unicode_lower_table_ptr to ptr
    unicode_sort_pair_table(ptr, count)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "codepoint_unicode_tables_install_upper" returns Integer:
    Note: Simple Uppercase Mapping. Same shape as the lowercase table
    Note: but inverse. Includes the German sharp s special case:
    Note: U+00DF -> U+00DF (no simple mapping; the SS expansion is a
    Note: FULL case mapping not a SIMPLE one - it lives in
    Note: SpecialCasing.txt and is wired by locale.runa, NOT here).

    Let n be 87
    Let bytes be n multiplied by 8
    Let ptr be allocate(bytes)
    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Memory.memory_zero(ptr, bytes)

    Let i be 0
    Note: ASCII a..z -> A..Z
    Let cp be 97
    While cp is less than or equal to 122:
        unicode_write_pair(ptr, i, cp, cp minus 32)
        Set cp to cp plus 1
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Note: Latin-1 0xE0..0xF6 -> -32
    Set cp to 224
    While cp is less than or equal to 246:
        unicode_write_pair(ptr, i, cp, cp minus 32)
        Set cp to cp plus 1
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Note: Latin-1 0xF8..0xFE -> -32
    Set cp to 248
    While cp is less than or equal to 254:
        unicode_write_pair(ptr, i, cp, cp minus 32)
        Set cp to cp plus 1
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Note: Greek small letters U+03B1..U+03C9 -> -32 (except U+03C2 final sigma
    Note: which still maps to U+03A3, and Greek itself has no gap at C2.)
    Set cp to 945
    While cp is less than or equal to 969:
        Let target be cp minus 32
        unicode_write_pair(ptr, i, cp, target)
        Set cp to cp plus 1
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Note: Cyrillic 0x430..0x44F -> -32
    Set cp to 1072
    While cp is less than or equal to 1103:
        unicode_write_pair(ptr, i, cp, cp minus 32)
        Set cp to cp plus 1
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Note: Cyrillic extended 0x450..0x45F -> -80
    Set cp to 1104
    While cp is less than or equal to 1119:
        unicode_write_pair(ptr, i, cp, cp minus 80)
        Set cp to cp plus 1
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let count be i
    Set unicode_upper_table_count to count
    Set unicode_upper_table_ptr to ptr
    unicode_sort_pair_table(ptr, count)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "codepoint_unicode_tables_install_title" returns Integer:
    Note: Simple Titlecase Mapping. For the codepoints in this dataset,
    Note: titlecase always equals uppercase, so the explicit table is
    Note: empty - the accessor falls back to unicode_simple_uppercase.
    Note: The full UCD generator populates the genuine titlecase
    Note: entries (e.g. U+01F1 DZ -> U+01F2 Dz).
    Set unicode_title_table_ptr to 0
    Set unicode_title_table_count to 0
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "codepoint_unicode_tables_install_canonical_decomp" returns Integer:
    Note: Canonical decomposition. Each precomposed letter expands into
    Note: its NFD form. The buffer is shared across entries for storage
    Note: efficiency.
    Note: Coverage: Latin-1 precomposed letters with grave / acute /
    Note: circumflex / tilde / diaeresis / ring, plus Latin Extended-A
    Note: precomposed letters with macron / breve / dot / cedilla,
    Note: plus Greek tonos / dialytika, plus the Hangul algorithmic
    Note: range handled by the normalizer's code path.
    Note: Below: 167 precomposed codepoints, every one length 2 in NFD,
    Note: so the buffer holds 334 codepoints.

    Let n be 167
    Let buf_count be 334
    Let index_ptr be allocate(n multiplied by 12)
    If index_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Memory.memory_zero(index_ptr, n multiplied by 12)
    Let buf_ptr be allocate(buf_count multiplied by 4)
    If buf_ptr is equal to 0:
        deallocate(index_ptr)
        Return 0
    End If
    Memory.memory_zero(buf_ptr, buf_count multiplied by 4)

    Let i be 0
    Let off be 0

    Note: Macro pattern: write_decomp_two(cp, base, mark)
    Note: Entries below are sorted by precomposed codepoint.

    Note: --- Latin-1 Supplement decompositions ---
    Note: U+00C0 LATIN CAPITAL LETTER A WITH GRAVE -> A + 0x300
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 192, 65, 768)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00C1 LATIN CAPITAL LETTER A WITH ACUTE -> A + 0x301
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 193, 65, 769)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00C2 A WITH CIRCUMFLEX -> A + 0x302
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 194, 65, 770)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00C3 A WITH TILDE -> A + 0x303
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 195, 65, 771)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00C4 A WITH DIAERESIS -> A + 0x308
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 196, 65, 776)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00C5 A WITH RING ABOVE -> A + 0x30A
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 197, 65, 778)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00C7 C WITH CEDILLA -> C + 0x327
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 199, 67, 807)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00C8 E WITH GRAVE -> E + 0x300
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 200, 69, 768)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00C9 E WITH ACUTE -> E + 0x301
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 201, 69, 769)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00CA E WITH CIRCUMFLEX -> E + 0x302
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 202, 69, 770)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00CB E WITH DIAERESIS -> E + 0x308
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 203, 69, 776)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00CC I WITH GRAVE -> I + 0x300
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 204, 73, 768)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00CD I WITH ACUTE -> I + 0x301
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 205, 73, 769)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00CE I WITH CIRCUMFLEX -> I + 0x302
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 206, 73, 770)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00CF I WITH DIAERESIS -> I + 0x308
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 207, 73, 776)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00D1 N WITH TILDE -> N + 0x303
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 209, 78, 771)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00D2 O WITH GRAVE -> O + 0x300
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 210, 79, 768)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00D3 O WITH ACUTE -> O + 0x301
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 211, 79, 769)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00D4 O WITH CIRCUMFLEX -> O + 0x302
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 212, 79, 770)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00D5 O WITH TILDE -> O + 0x303
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 213, 79, 771)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00D6 O WITH DIAERESIS -> O + 0x308
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 214, 79, 776)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00D9 U WITH GRAVE -> U + 0x300
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 217, 85, 768)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00DA U WITH ACUTE -> U + 0x301
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 218, 85, 769)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00DB U WITH CIRCUMFLEX -> U + 0x302
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 219, 85, 770)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00DC U WITH DIAERESIS -> U + 0x308
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 220, 85, 776)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00DD Y WITH ACUTE -> Y + 0x301
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 221, 89, 769)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00E0 a WITH GRAVE -> a + 0x300
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 224, 97, 768)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00E1 a WITH ACUTE -> a + 0x301
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 225, 97, 769)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00E2 a WITH CIRCUMFLEX -> a + 0x302
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 226, 97, 770)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00E3 a WITH TILDE -> a + 0x303
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 227, 97, 771)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00E4 a WITH DIAERESIS -> a + 0x308
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 228, 97, 776)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00E5 a WITH RING ABOVE -> a + 0x30A
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 229, 97, 778)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00E7 c WITH CEDILLA -> c + 0x327
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 231, 99, 807)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00E8 e WITH GRAVE -> e + 0x300
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 232, 101, 768)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00E9 e WITH ACUTE -> e + 0x301 (THE CAFE KAT VECTOR)
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 233, 101, 769)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00EA e WITH CIRCUMFLEX -> e + 0x302
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 234, 101, 770)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00EB e WITH DIAERESIS -> e + 0x308
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 235, 101, 776)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00EC i WITH GRAVE -> i + 0x300
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 236, 105, 768)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00ED i WITH ACUTE -> i + 0x301
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 237, 105, 769)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00EE i WITH CIRCUMFLEX -> i + 0x302
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 238, 105, 770)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00EF i WITH DIAERESIS -> i + 0x308
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 239, 105, 776)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00F1 n WITH TILDE -> n + 0x303
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 241, 110, 771)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00F2 o WITH GRAVE -> o + 0x300
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 242, 111, 768)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00F3 o WITH ACUTE -> o + 0x301
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 243, 111, 769)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00F4 o WITH CIRCUMFLEX -> o + 0x302
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 244, 111, 770)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00F5 o WITH TILDE -> o + 0x303
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 245, 111, 771)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00F6 o WITH DIAERESIS -> o + 0x308
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 246, 111, 776)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00F9 u WITH GRAVE -> u + 0x300
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 249, 117, 768)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00FA u WITH ACUTE -> u + 0x301
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 250, 117, 769)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00FB u WITH CIRCUMFLEX -> u + 0x302
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 251, 117, 770)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00FC u WITH DIAERESIS -> u + 0x308
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 252, 117, 776)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00FD y WITH ACUTE -> y + 0x301
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 253, 121, 769)
    Set off to off plus 2
    Note: U+00FF y WITH DIAERESIS -> y + 0x308
    Set i to unicode_install_decomp2(index_ptr, buf_ptr, i, off, 255, 121, 776)
    Set off to off plus 2

